SIMPLE: run
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Run
<hw>Run</hw> <pr>(r⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Ran</conjf> <pr>(r⟦acr⟧n)</pr> or
<conjf>Run</conjf>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Run</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Running</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>rinnen</ets>, <ets>rennen</ets> (imp. <ets>ran</ets>, p. p.
<ets>runnen</ets>, <ets>ronnen</ets>). AS. <ets>rinnan</ets> to flow
(imp. <ets>ran</ets>, p. p. <ets>gerunnen</ets>), and <ets>iernan</ets>,
<ets>irnan</ets>, to run (imp. <ets>orn</ets>, <ets>arn</ets>,
<ets>earn</ets>, p. p. <ets>urnen</ets>); akin to D. <ets>runnen</ets>,
<ets>rennen</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>rinnan</ets>, G. <ets>rinnen</ets>,
<ets>rennen</ets>, Icel. <ets>renna</ets>, <ets>rinna</ets>, Sw.
<ets>rinna</ets>, <ets>r⟦aum⟧nna</ets>, Dan. <ets>rinde</ets>,
<ets>rende</ets>, Goth. <ets>rinnan</ets>, and perh. to L.
<ets>oriri</ets> to rise, Gr. <grk>'orny`nai</grk> to stir up, rouse,
Skr. <ets>⟦rsdot⟧</ets> (cf. <er>Origin</er>), or perh. to L.
<ets>rivus</ets> brook (cf. <er>Rival</er>). ⟦root⟧11. Cf.
<er>Ember</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, <er>Rennet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To move, proceed, advance, pass, go, come, etc., swiftly, smoothly,
or with quick action; -- said of things animate or inanimate. Hence, to
flow, glide, or roll onward, as a stream, a snake, a wagon, etc.; to
move by quicker action than in walking, as a person, a horse, a
dog.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> Of voluntary or personal action: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To go
swiftly; to pass at a swift pace; to hasten.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧Ha, ha, the fox!⟦rdquo⟧ and after him they
<qex>ran</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>To flee, as from fear or danger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As from a bear a man would <qex>run</qex> for life.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To steal off; to depart secretly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>To contend in a race; hence, to enter into a
contest; to become a candidate; as, to <xex>run</xex> for
Congress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Know ye not that they which <qex>run</qex> in a race
<qex>run</qex> all, but one receiveth the prize? So <qex>run</qex>, that
ye may obtain.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. ix. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>To pass from one state or condition to another; to
come into a certain condition; -- often with <xex>in</xex> or
<xex>into</xex>; as, to <xex>run</xex> into evil practices; to
<xex>run</xex> in debt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have I not cause to rave and beat my breast, to rend my heart with
grief and <qex>run</qex> distracted?</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(f)</sd> <def>To exert continuous activity; to proceed; <as>as,
to <ex>run</ex> through life; to <ex>run</ex> in a circle</as>.</def>
<sd>(g)</sd> <def>To pass or go quickly in thought or conversation; as,
to <xex>run</xex> from one subject to another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Virgil, in his first Georgic, has <qex>run</qex> into a set of
precepts foreign to his subject.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(h)</sd> <def>To discuss; to continue to think or speak about
something; -- with <xex>on</xex>.</def> <sd>(i)</sd> <def>To make
numerous drafts or demands for payment, as upon a bank; -- with
<xex>on</xex>.</def> <sd>(j)</sd> <def>To creep, as serpents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> Of involuntary motion: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To flow, as a
liquid; to ascend or descend; to course; <as>as, rivers <ex>run</ex> to
the sea; sap <ex>runs</ex> up in the spring; her blood <ex>ran</ex>
cold</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To proceed along a surface; to
extend; to spread.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fire <qex>ran</qex> along upon the ground.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
ix. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To become fluid; to melt; to fuse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As wax dissolves, as ice begins to <qex>run</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sussex iron ores <qex>run</qex> freely in the fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>To turn, as a wheel; to revolve on an axis or
pivot; as, a wheel <xex>runs</xex> swiftly round.</def> <sd>(e)</sd>
<def>To travel; to make progress; to be moved by mechanical means; to
go; <as>as, the steamboat <ex>runs</ex> regularly to Albany; the train
<ex>runs</ex> to Chicago</as>.</def> <sd>(f)</sd> <def>To extend; to
reach; <as>as, the road <ex>runs</ex> from Philadelphia to New York; the
memory of man <ex>runneth</ex> not to the contrary</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She saw with joy the line immortal <qex>run</qex>,⟦br⟧
Each sire impressed, and glaring in his son.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(g)</sd> <def>To go back and forth from place to place; to ply;
as, the stage <xex>runs</xex> between the hotel and the
station.</def><-- same as (e)? --> <sd>(h)</sd> <def>To make progress;
to proceed; to pass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As fast as our time <qex>runs</qex>, we should be very glad in
most part of our lives that it <qex>ran</qex> much faster.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(i)</sd> <def>To continue in operation; to be kept in action or
motion; <as>as, this engine <ex>runs</ex> night and day; the mill
<ex>runs</ex> six days in the week</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When we desire anything, our minds <qex>run</qex> wholly on the
good circumstances of it; when it is obtained, our minds run wholly on
the bad ones.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(j)</sd> <def>To have a course or direction; as, a line
<xex>runs</xex> east and west.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where the generally allowed practice <qex>runs</qex> counter to
it.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Little is the wisdom, where the flight⟦br⟧
So <qex>runs</qex> against all reason.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(k)</sd> <def>To be in form thus, as a combination of
words.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king's ordinary style <qex>runneth</qex>, ⟦ldquo⟧Our sovereign
lord the king.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Sanderson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(l)</sd> <def>To be popularly known; to be generally
received.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men gave them their own names, by which they <qex>run</qex> a
great while in Rome.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither was he ignorant what report <qex>ran</qex> of himself.</q>
<rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1261 --></p>

<p><sd>(m)</sd> <def>To have growth or development; <as>as, boys and
girls <ex>run</ex> up rapidly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the richness of the ground cause turnips to <qex>run</qex> to
leaves.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(n)</sd> <def>To tend, as to an effect or consequence; to
incline.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man's nature <qex>runs</qex> either to herbs or weeds.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Temperate climates <qex>run</qex> into moderate governments.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(o)</sd> <def>To spread and blend together; to unite; <as>as,
colors <ex>run</ex> in washing</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the middle of a rainbow the colors are . . . distinguished, but
near the borders they <qex>run</qex> into one another.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(p)</sd> <def>To have a legal course; to be attached; to continue
in force, effect, or operation; to follow; to go in company; <as>as,
certain covenants <ex>run</ex> with the land</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Customs <qex>run</qex> only upon our goods imported or exported,
and that but once for all; whereas interest <qex>runs</qex> as well upon
our ships as goods, and must be yearly paid.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Child.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(q)</sd> <def>To continue without falling due; to hold good;
<as>as, a note has thirty days to <ex>run</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(r)</sd>
<def>To discharge pus or other matter; <as>as, an ulcer
<ex>runs</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(s)</sd> <def>To be played on the stage a
number of successive days or nights; <as>as, the piece <ex>ran</ex> for
six months</as>.</def> <sd>(t)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To sail
before the wind, in distinction from reaching or sailing closehauled; --
said of vessels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Specifically, of a horse: To move rapidly in a gait
in which each leg acts in turn as a propeller and a supporter, and in
which for an instant all the limbs are gathered in the air under the
body.</def> <rj><au>Stillman (The Horse in Motion).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Athletics)</fld> <def>To move rapidly by springing
steps so that there is an instant in each step when neither foot touches
the ground; -- so distinguished from <xex>walking</xex> in athletic
competition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>As things run</b></col>, <cd>according to the usual
order, conditions, quality, etc.; on the average; without selection or
specification.</cd> -- <col><b>To let run</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>to allow to pass or move freely; to slacken or loosen.</cd> --
<col><b>To run after</b></col>, <cd>to pursue or follow; to search for;
to endeavor to find or obtain; <as>as, <ex>to run after</ex>
similes</as>.</cd> <au>Locke.</au> -- <col><b>To run away</b></col>,
<cd>to flee; to escape; to elope; to run without control or
guidance.</cd> -- <col><b>To run away with</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To convey away hurriedly; to accompany in escape or elopement.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To drag rapidly and with violence; <as>as, a horse
<ex>runs away with</ex> a carriage</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To run
down</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To cease to work or operate on account
of the exhaustion of the motive power; -- said of clocks, watches,
etc.</cd><-- batteries --> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To decline in condition;
<as>as, <ex>to run down</ex> in health</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To run down
a coast</b></col>, <cd>to sail along it.</cd> -- <col><b>To run for an
office</b></col>, <cd>to stand as a candidate for an office.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>To run in</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To run
into</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To enter; to step in</cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To come in collision with.</cd> -- <col><b>To run
into</b></col> <cd>To meet, by chance; <as>as, I <ex>ran into</ex> my
brother at the grocery store</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To run in
trust</b></col>, <cd>to run in debt; to get credit.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> -- <col><b>To run in with</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To close; to comply; to agree with.</cd> <mark>[R.]</mark> <au>T.
Baker.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To make toward; to near;
to sail close to; as, <xex>to run in with</xex> the land.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>To run mad</b></col>, <col><b>To run mad after</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>To run mad on</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under
<er>Mad</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To run on</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
be continued; as, their accounts had <xex>run on</xex> for a year or two
without a settlement.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To talk incessantly</cd>.
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To continue a course</cd>. <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To press
with jokes or ridicule; to abuse with sarcasm; to bear hard on</cd>.
<sd>(e)</sd> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <cd>To be continued in the same lines,
without making a break or beginning a new paragraph</cd>. -- <col><b>To
run out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To come to an end; to expire;
<as>as, the lease <ex>runs out</ex> at Michaelmas</as>.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To extend; to spread</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧Insectile animals . .
. <xex>run</xex> all <xex>out</xex> into legs.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Hammond.</au>
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To expatiate; as, <xex>to run out</xex> into beautiful
digressions.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To be wasted or exhausted; to become
poor; to become extinct; as, an estate managed without economy will soon
<xex>run out</xex>.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And had her stock been less, no doubt⟦br⟧
She must have long ago <qex>run out</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>To run over</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To overflow;
<as>as, a cup <ex>runs over</ex>, or the liquor <ex>runs
over</ex></as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To go over, examine, or rehearse
cursorily</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To ride or drive over; <as>as, <ex>to
run over</ex> a child</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To run riot</b></col>,
<cd>to go to excess.</cd> -- <col><b>To run through</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To go through hastily; <as>as <ex>to run through</ex> a
book</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To spend wastefully; as, to run through
an estate.</cd> -- <col><b>To run to seed</b></col>, <cd>to expend or
exhaust vitality in producing seed, as a plant; figuratively and
colloquially, to cease growing; to lose vital force, as the body or
mind.</cd> -- <col><b>To run up</b></col>, <cd>to rise; to swell; to
grow; to increase; as, accounts of goods credited <xex>run up</xex> very
fast.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But these, having been untrimmed for many years, had <qex>run
up</qex> into great bushes, or rather dwarf trees.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>To run with</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To be drenched
with, so that streams flow; <as>as, the streets <ex>ran with</ex>
blood</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To flow while charged with some
foreign substance</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧Its rivers <xex>ran with</xex>
gold.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>J. H. Newman.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Run</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Run
<hw>Run</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause
to run (in the various senses of <er>Run</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>);
<as>as, to <ex>run</ex> a horse; to <ex>run</ex> a stage; to
<ex>run</ex> a machine; to <ex>run</ex> a rope through a
block</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pursue in thought; to carry in
contemplation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>run</qex> the world back to its first original.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would gladly understand the formation of a soul, and
<qex>run</qex> it up to its ⟦ldquo⟧punctum saliens.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Collier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to enter; to thrust; <as>as, to
<ex>run</ex> a sword into or through the body; to <ex>run</ex> a nail
into the foot</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>run</qex> your head into the lion's mouth.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Having <qex>run</qex> his fingers through his hair.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To drive or force; to cause, or permit, to be
driven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>ran</qex> the ship aground.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xxvii.
41.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A talkative person <qex>runs</qex> himself upon great
inconveniences by blabbing out his own or other's secrets.</q>
<rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Others, accustomed to retired speculations, <qex>run</qex> natural
philosophy into metaphysical notions.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To fuse; to shape; to mold; to cast; <as>as, to
<ex>run</ex> bullets, and the like</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The purest gold must be <qex>run</qex> and washed.</q>
<rj><qau>Felton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To cause to be drawn; to mark out; to indicate; to
determine; <as>as, to <ex>run</ex> a line</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To cause to pass, or evade, official restrictions;
to smuggle; -- said of contraband or dutiable goods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Heavy impositions . . . are a strong temptation of
<qex>running</qex> goods.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To go through or accomplish by running; <as>as, to
<ex>run</ex> a race; to <ex>run</ex> a certain career</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To cause to stand as a candidate for office; to
support for office; <as>as, to <ex>run</ex> some one for
Congress</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To encounter or incur, as a danger or risk; <as>as,
to <ex>run</ex> the risk of losing one's life. See <ex>To run the
chances</ex>, below</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>runneth</xex> two
dangers.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If we don't succeed, we <ex>run the risk</ex> of failure.</q>
<qau>Dan Quail</qau>.⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To put at hazard; to venture; to risk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He would himself be in the Highlands to receive them, and
<qex>run</qex> his fortune with them.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>To discharge; to emit; to give forth copiously; to
be bathed with; <as>as, the pipe or faucet <ex>runs</ex> hot
water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At the base of Pompey's statua,⟦br⟧
Which all the while <qex>ran</qex> blood, great Caesar fell.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>To be charged with, or to contain much of, while
flowing; <as>as, the rivers <ex>ran</ex> blood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>To conduct; to manage; to carry on; <as>as, to
<ex>run</ex> a factory or a hotel</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <def>To tease with sarcasms and ridicule.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <def>To sew, as a seam, by passing the needle through
material in a continuous line, generally taking a series of stitches on
the needle at the same time.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>17.</sn> <def>To migrate or move in schools; -- said of fish;
esp., to ascend a river in order to spawn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>18.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>To strike (the ball) in such a
way as to cause it to run along the ground, as when approaching a
hole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To run a blockade</b></col>, <cd>to get to, or away from,
a blockaded port in safety.</cd> -- <col><b>To run down</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Hunting)</fld> <cd>To chase till the object pursued
is captured or exhausted; <as>as, <ex>to run down</ex> a stag</as></cd>.
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To run against and sink, as a
vessel</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To crush; to overthrow; to overbear</cd>.
⟦ldquo⟧Religion is <xex>run down</xex> by the license of these
times.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Berkeley.</au> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To disparage; to
traduce.</cd> <au>F. W. Newman.</au> -- <col><b>To run hard</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To press in competition; <as>as, <ex>to run</ex> one
<ex>hard</ex> in a race</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To urge or press
importunately</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To banter severely.</cd> --
<col><b>To run into the ground</b></col>, <cd>to carry to an absurd
extreme; to overdo.</cd> <mark>[Slang, U.S.]</mark><-- also, to operate
a machine (as a car) without maintenance, until it malfunctions or
becomes useless --> -- <col><b>To run off</b></col>, <cd>to cause to
flow away, as a charge of molten metal from a furnace.</cd> --
<col><b>To run on</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>to carry on or
continue, as the type for a new sentence, without making a break or
commencing a new paragraph.</cd> -- <col><b>To run out</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To thrust or push out; to extend.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>To waste; to exhaust; <as>as, <ex>to run out</ex> an
estate</as>.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <cd>To put out
while running between two bases. Also called <col><b>to run
out</b></col>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To run the chances</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>To run one's chances</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to
encounter all the risks of a certain course.</cd> -- <col><b>To run
through</b></col>, <cd>to transfix; to pierce, as with a sword.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧[He] was <xex>run through</xex> the body by the man who had asked
his advice.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au> -- <col><b>To run up</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To thrust up, as anything long and slender.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To increase; to enlarge by additions, as an
account</cd>.<-- e.g. to incur a debt, as to <ex>run up</ex> a bill -->
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To erect hastily, as a building</cd>.</cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Run</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Run
<hw>Run</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
running; <as>as, a long <ex>run</ex>; a good <ex>run</ex>; a quick
<ex>run</ex>; to go on the <ex>run</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small stream; a brook; a creek.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which runs or flows in the course of a certain
operation, or during a certain time; <as>as, a <ex>run</ex> of must in
wine making; the first <ex>run</ex> of sap in a maple
orchard</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A course; a series; that which continues in a
certain course or series; <as>as, a <ex>run</ex> of good or bad
luck</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They who made their arrangements in the first <qex>run</qex> of
misadventure . . . put a seal on their calamities.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>State of being current; currency;
popularity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is impossible for detached papers to have a general
<qex>run</qex>, or long continuance, if not diversified with humor.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Continued repetition on the stage; -- said of a
play; <as>as, to have a <ex>run</ex> of a hundred successive
nights</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A canting, mawkish play . . . had an immense <qex>run</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A continuing urgent demand; especially, a pressure
on a bank or treasury for payment of its notes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A range or extent of ground for feeding stock;
<as>as, a sheep <ex>run</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Howitt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The aftermost part
of a vessel's hull where it narrows toward the stern, under the
quarter.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The distance sailed by a ship; <as>as,
a good <ex>run</ex>; a <ex>run</ex> of fifty miles</as>.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>A voyage; <as>as, a <ex>run</ex> to
China</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A pleasure excursion; a trip.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I think of giving her a <qex>run</qex> in London.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The horizontal distance to
which a drift may be carried, either by license of the proprietor of a
mine or by the nature of the formation; also, the direction which a vein
of ore or other substance takes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A roulade, or series of running
tones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>The greatest degree of swiftness
in marching. It is executed upon the same principles as the
double-quick, but with greater speed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>The act of migrating, or ascending a river to
spawn; -- said of fish; also, an assemblage or school of fishes which
migrate, or ascend a river for the purpose of spawning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <fld>(Sport)</fld> <def>In baseball, a complete circuit
of the bases made by a player, which enables him to score one point;
also, the point thus scored; in cricket, a passing from one wicket to
the other, by which one point is scored; <as>as, a player made three
<ex>runs</ex>; the side went out with two hundred <ex>runs</ex>; the
Yankees scored three <ex>runs</ex> in the seventh inning</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ⟦ldquo⟧<qex>runs</qex>⟦rdquo⟧ are made from wicket to wicket,
the batsmen interchanging ends at each <qex>run</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>R.
A. Proctor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <def>A pair or set of millstones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>17.</sn> <fld>(Piquet, Cribbage, etc.)</fld> <def>A number of
cards of the same suit in sequence; <as>as, a <ex>run</ex> of four in
hearts</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>18.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The movement
communicated to a golf ball by running.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The
distance a ball travels after touching the ground from a
stroke.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>At the long run</b></col>, <it>now, commonly</it>,
<col><b>In the long run</b></col></mcol>, <cd>in or during the whole
process or course of things taken together; in the final result; in the
end; finally.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Man] starts the inferior of the brute animals, but he surpasses
them <qex>in the long run</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J. H.
Newman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>Home run</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A running or
returning toward home, or to the point from which the start was
made.</cd> Cf. <cref>Home stretch</cref>. <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Baseball)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Home</er>.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>The run</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>The common
run</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>The run of the mill</b></col>
etc.</mcol>, <cd>ordinary persons; the generality or average of people
or things; also, that which ordinarily occurs; ordinary current, course,
or kind.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>I saw nothing else that is superior to <qex>the common run</qex>
of parks.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Burns never dreamed of looking down on others as beneath him,
merely because he was conscious of his own vast superiority to <qex>the
common run</qex> of men.</q> <rj><qau>Prof. Wilson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His whole appearance was something out of <qex>the common
run</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>To let go by the run</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
loosen and let run freely, as lines; to let fall without restraint, as a
sail.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Run</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Run
<hw>Run</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Melted, or made from molten
material; cast in a mold; <as>as, <ex>run</ex> butter; <ex>run</ex> iron
or lead</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Smuggled; <as>as, <ex>run</ex> goods</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Miss Edgeworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Run steel</b></col>, <cd>malleable iron castings. See
under <er>Malleable</er>.</cd> <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Runagate</ent>⟦br⟧
